  "prompt": "Why are there two capital letters in the surname McCall?",
  "response": "The surname McCall features two capital letters due to its origins in Scottish and Irish naming conventions. \"Mc\" or \"Mac\" is a prefix meaning \"son of,\" and the subsequent part of the name (in this case \"Call\") represents the ancestor's name. This structure is common in Gaelic surnames. \n\nIn many cases, the \"Mc\" or \"Mac\" is capitalized to distinguish it from the rest of the name, emphasizing its role as a prefix. In some contexts, the \"C\" in \"Call\" is also capitalized to maintain consistency in styling, especially in formal or official documents. Therefore, \"Mc\" and \"Call\" are both capitalized to honor the tradition and to make the surname immediately recognizable.",
